#Some default functions to ease the data exploration
def int_min(param):
    return np.iinfo(param).min

def int_max(param):
    return np.iinfo(param).max

def flo_min(param):
    return np.finfo(param).min

def flo_max(param):
    return np.finfo(param).max

def decrease_mem(in_table, verbose = True):
    data_types = ['int16', 'int32', 'int64', 'float16', 'float32', 'float64']
    initial_mem_val = in_table.memory_usage().sum() / 2**20 #Calculate memory usage of complete column 
                                                            #and dividng it by 2^20 to convert it into Mb    
    for c in in_table.columns:
        column_type = in_table[c].dtypes
        if column_type in data_types:
            min_val = in_table[c].min()
            max_val = in_table[c].max()
            if str(column_type)[:3] == 'int':
                if min_val > int_min(np.int8) and max_val < int_max(np.int8): #calling another fn int_min & int_max
                    in_table[c] = in_table[c].astype(np.int8)
                elif min_val > int_min(np.int16) and max_val < int_max(np.int16):
                    in_table[c] = in_table[c].astype(np.int16)
                elif min_val > int_min(np.int32) and max_val < int_max(np.int32):
                    in_table[c] = in_table[c].astype(np.int32)
                elif min_val > int_min(np.int64) and max_val < int_max(np.int64):
                    in_table[c] = in_table[c].astype(np.int64)  
            elif min_val > flo_min(np.float16) and max_val < flo_max(np.float16):
                    in_table[c] = in_table[c].astype(np.float16)
            elif min_val > flo_min(np.float32) and max_val < flo_max(np.float32):
                    in_table[c] = in_table[c].astype(np.float32)
            else: in_table[c] = in_table[c].astype(np.float64)
                
    mem_aftr_ops = in_table.memory_usage().sum() / 2**20
    if verbose: print('Mem. usage decreased to {:5.2f} Mb ({:.1f}% reduction)'.
          format(mem_aftr_ops, ((initial_mem_val - mem_aftr_ops) / initial_mem_val)* 100))
    return in_table

def EDA(df_table):
    summ = pd.DataFrame(df_table.dtypes, columns=['Data Type'])
    summ = summ.reset_index()
    summ['Name'] = summ['index']
    summ = summ[['Name', 'Data Type']]
    summ['Missing Values'] = df_table.isnull().sum().values
    summ['Unique'] = df_table.nunique().values
    summ['First Value'] = df_table.loc[0].values
    summ['Second Value'] = df_table.loc[1].values
    summ['Third Value'] = df_table.loc[2].values
    summ['Minimum Value'] = df_table.min().values
    summ['Maximum Value'] = df_table.max().values
    #summary['Uniques'] = df.nunique().values
    
    for name in summ['Name'].value_counts().index:
        summ.loc[summ['Name'] == name, 'Entropy'] = round(stats.entropy(df_table[name].value_counts(normalize=True), 
                                                                        base=2),2)
    return summ

def plot_stack(column_1, column_2):
    plot_stck=pd.crosstab(index=column_1, columns=column_2)
    plot_stck.plot(kind='bar', figsize=(8,8), stacked=True)
    return

#Since, we have a datetime column with all the timestamp information. We will extract information from this column for

#creating from datetime, columns like date, hour, month, weekday, etc.

mod_data['datetime'] = pd.to_datetime(mod_data['datetime'])
mod_data['date'], mod_data['hour'] = mod_data['datetime'].apply(lambda x: x.date()), mod_data['datetime'].apply(lambda x: x.time())
mod_data['month'] = mod_data['date'].apply(lambda dateString : calendar.month_name[datetime.strptime(str(dateString),"%Y-%m-%d").month])
mod_data['weekday'] = mod_data['date'].apply(lambda dateString : calendar.day_name[datetime.strptime(str(dateString),"%Y-%m-%d").weekday()])
mod_data['hour'] = mod_data['hour'].apply(lambda x: x.hour)

Predicting Zero values in column "windspeed"¶

It can be observed that there are a lot of zero values in the column windspeed. We can use RandomForrestRegressor with default values to predict these values!

In [10]:
wind_null = mod_data[mod_data["windspeed"] == float(0)].copy()
wind_not_null = mod_data[mod_data["windspeed"] != float(0)].copy()

# predicting zero values in windspeed using random forest regressor

rfModel_wind = RandomForestRegressor(n_estimators=1200, max_depth=180, max_features='auto')

windColumns = ["season","weather","humidity","month","temp","year","atemp"]

rfModel_wind.fit(wind_not_null[windColumns], wind_not_null["windspeed"])

wind0Values = rfModel_wind.predict(X = wind_null[windColumns])
wind_null["windspeed"] = wind0Values

mod_data = wind_not_null.append(wind_null)
mod_data.reset_index(inplace=True)
mod_data.drop('index', inplace=True, axis=1)
mod_data.sort_values(by=['datetime'], inplace=True)

# As it can be seen in the above figure that there is a high demand of bikes at around 8am and 5pm-8pm on a working day. Also, \n
# on non-working days, the peak time is usually between 10am-7pm. Hence, we can extract a feature representing peak demand as 1.

mod_data['peak_time'] = 0
mod_data.loc[((mod_data['workingday'] == 1) & ((mod_data['hour'] == 8) | (mod_data['hour'] == 12))), 'peak_time'] = 1
mod_data.loc[(mod_data['workingday'] == 1) & ((mod_data['hour'] >= 17) & (mod_data['hour'] < 20)), 'peak_time'] = 1
mod_data.loc[(mod_data['workingday'] == 0) & ((mod_data['hour'] >= 10) & (mod_data['hour'] <= 19)), 'peak_time'] = 1

# Creating a seperate columns representing favourable condition, at these conditions the count would be more!
# Similarly creating columns representing harsh conditions!
mod_data['best_condition'] = 0
mod_data['not_fav'] = 0
mod_data.loc[(mod_data['temp'] > 27) & (mod_data['windspeed'] < 30), 'best_condition'] = 1
mod_data.loc[(mod_data['workingday'] == 1) & (mod_data['humidity'] >= 60), 'not_fav' ] = 1

# Since, the hour column is categorical and cyclic. We can transform it using sine and cosine transformations, \n
# So that it represents cyclic nature of the feature and so that our alogrithm does not differentiate much between 0 and 23.

mod_data['sine_hr'] = mod_data['hour'].apply(lambda x : np.sin(2.*np.pi*x/24.))
mod_data['cos_hr'] = mod_data['hour'].apply(lambda x : np.cos(2.*np.pi*x/24.))

mod_data.plot.scatter('sine_hr','cos_hr').set_aspect('equal')
#below figure represents that the both columns combined reporesents the cyclic nature of the column hour!

#checking correlation of variables with each other
corr_col = ['season', 'holiday', 'workingday', 'weather', 'temp',
            'atemp', 'humidity', 'windspeed', 'casual', 'registered', 'count',
            'date', 'hour', 'month', 'weekday', 'year',
            'peak_time', 'weekoff_count', 'best_condition', 'not_fav', 'sine_hr', 'cos_hr']
bike_corr = mod_data[corr_col].corr()
mask = np.array(bike_corr)
mask[np.tril_indices_from(mask)] = False
fig,ax= plt.subplots()
fig.set_size_inches(15,10)
sns.heatmap(bike_corr, mask=mask,annot=True, cbar=True)
